The  angles are ones that I can see people enjoying, though I've been tired of magical Nazi tech for quite a long time now. I've never quite been comfortable with the subconscious admiration for the technological prowess of the Third Reich that comes with that sort of thing, even though that's not what's intended in 99% of depictions.

What's really making this not work for me is the fact that this hinges on a feeling of pity and sympathy for the automaton, which is locked in a routine in which it apparently feels overwhelming nurturing and caring emotions for something that will never come into being. There's nothing inherently wrong with going for that sort of story. But I personally am having a very difficult time being all that sad that the SS Class of 1971 will never come to pass. More than that, I am having a difficult time caring that a robot, programmed with Nazi attitudes about  and all the attendant racial purity nonsense that comes with that, will never know the joy of raising a nursery full of baby Aryan warriors. And I get the strong impression that I am supposed to care about that (as apparently a lot of people do here).

This isn't a commentary on the author, who I'm quite sure does not hold any sympathy for the political system in which this anomaly operates. But robots who want nothing more than to build up the Master Race, complete with Tony Stark glowing swastikas in their chests, make a poor subject if what I'm supposed to feel is anything other than contempt for the character. Without that emotional connection, this is just another entry in a trope that I don't have a whole lot of interest in.







