How sure are you that it ? If it wasn't sapient, would it have commented on the fact that the babies lie unmoving at the bottom of their tanks?
附加记录：    

It also recognizes what death is, but claims that it doesn't apply to the clearly-dead experiments since they are neither  or soldiers. Stillness indicates death. Death occurs only to Untermenschen or soldiers. The experiments are neither. Therefore, they are not dead, and the stillness is ultimately irrelevant for diagnostic purposes.

This is a very rigid if-then line of logic that we typically see in computers and machines, and it commenting on the stillness may be an attempt to  what is clearly a misdiagnosis from another doctor. Outside of being completely grief-stricken or otherwise disconnected from reality, a human would immediately see the flaw in the if-then logic line, and at the very least not dismiss the apparant contradiction out-of-hand.

Also, remember that it apparently stores programs on record-like disks, and its implied that it cannot take any actions beyond the programming on that disk. If it cannot surpass or amend the programming it is running on, then it can't really be self-aware, especially if it acts as a paperweight without a program (which seems to be the case here).

If it is sapient, bringing attention to the fact that it taking care of things that have long-since died could have snapped it out of its current mode of thought. Either that, or it's completely batshit insane and trying to cling onto the one semblance of normalcy it has, which isn't really all that well-supported in the article.







